thinking:
We need to assess if visualization described is misleading. The analysis says bar graph of % of global population lost to pandemics, with numbers like Black Death 42.1%, Plague of Justinian 25%, Antonie Plague 15%, etc. Several issues: Data validity – percentages are likely inaccurate or based on uncertain estimates; many events have "various dates", and percentages of world population lost are not directly comparable because global population estimates differ over time, and mortality percentages may be based on different baselines (e.g., regional vs global). Also, they are mixing historical estimates with modern pandemics, but using same metric (percentage of global population) which may be misleading because data for ancient pandemics are highly uncertain. Also cherry-picking: they selected pandemics that support narrative that COVID less severe; many other pandemics (e.g., 1918 flu estimated 2-3% of world pop; they put 3% which is okay). But they omitted COVID data entirely, maybe implying it's lower than Spanish flu but not shown. That could be cherry-picking or omission.

Potential error: Issues with data validity – uncertain estimates, no sources. Also failure to account for statistical nuance – using percentage of global population doesn't capture total deaths, and differences in population size over time, also different time spans. Also possibly misleading encoding? Bar graph of percentages likely fine. Could be truncated axis? Not specified; maybe y-axis starts at 0? Unknown.

Thus we can mark misleading due to data validity and cherry-picking, possibly failure to account for statistical nuance. Also possibly "Unclear encoding" if the graph doesn't clarify that percentages are of world population at time of pandemic, not current.

Intentional? Likely the creator intends to downplay COVID by comparing to past; could be intentional rhetorical framing. But could also be unintentional due to lack of nuance. I think moderate confidence of intentional (maybe to argue COVID not unprecedented). Provide confidence ~70.

Rhetoric types: Information Access Rhetoric – selection of pandemics and omission of COVID, yes. Provenance Rhetoric – likely absent (no sources), so not present. Mapping Rhetoric – mapping percentages to bar length, appropriate but perhaps emphasizes differences; exists. Linguistic-Based Rhetoric – title "Covid deaths in context" frames interpretation, yes. Procedural Rhetoric – likely none (static bar graph). Provide confidence per type.
